Are you experiencing low or no suction on the Harmony Manual Pump? Let's troubleshoot together mama! 1) Check the O-ring: Double-check that the O-ring (that tiny white rubber band) isn’t missing, damaged, or broken—it’s a small but mighty part! 2) Align the Stem: Make sure the yellow stem (the plastic peice connected to the diaphragm with the line on it) is properly aligned with the diaphragm. Keep that line parallel with the tabs on the diaphragm for optimal suction If you’ve checked both of these and are still having trouble, please send us a DM, and our customer care team will be happy to assist you! 💛 #harmonypump #manualhandpump #breastfeeding #pumping #medelaharmony #medela #harmonyhandpump #harmonymanualpump

Bending and moving after your C-section got you feeling squeamish? 😬 You aren’t alone! Most new moms struggle to bend forward for several weeks after a cesarean birth. Replacing duckbill valves and diaphragms every 1 to 3 months is crucial for maintaining the efficiency and hygiene of your breast pump because - Maintains Suction Efficiency: Duckbill valves and diaphragms are vital for creating a tight seal and maintaining the suction power of the breast pump. Over time, they can become worn or stretched, leading to decreased suction efficiency, which can reduce the amount of breast milk expressed during pumping sessions. - Prevent Contamination: Regular use of breast pumps can lead to the deposition of milk residues or the growth of bacteria and mold in the parts, including valves and diaphragms. Replacing these components frequently ensures that the pump remains hygienic, limiting the risk of contamination of the milk that could potentially harm the baby! 🤱 #foryou #zomeez2 #zomee #fyp #breastpump #momtiktok #pregnantlife #breastfeeding

We get it... It's hard to go with the flow right after giving birth! Many moms wonder when and if their milk will come in! Don't worry, you've been producing colostrum (the first milk) since you were around 20 weeks pregnant! Once your baby and the placenta have been delivered, your body knows that you are now no longer pregnant and those pregnancy hormones rapidly decrease, allowing for the lactation hormones to take over. For most women, this is very easy to recognize; your breasts will feel much fuller, heavier, and maybe even a little warmer and sometimes tender. Your milk will usually come in anywhere between 24 and 72 hours after birth.

Trying to maximize your milk output with the Pump In Style? You've got this! Here's a break down to help you find your perfect pumping rhythm. ✨ Find Your Maximum Comfort Vacuum (MCV): • It's all about comfort! Don't crank it up to 10! • Increase suction gradually until it feels "almost uncomfortable" then back down one level. That's your sweet spot! Double Down on Letdowns: • Milk flow can be a marathon, not a sprint! • Use the stimulation mode throughout your session to trigger multiple letdowns and maximize output. Play with the Settings: • There's no one-size-fits-all setting! Experiment to find what works best for YOU. 🌟 Bonus Tip: Note that the pump always begins in the Stimulation Phase at level 4. video: @maybeitsbrit

If you are trying to breastfeed or pump, but not producing enough milk….don’t give up yet. Follow these steps👇👇👇 1. Your flange might not be the right size. Using the wrong size flange may pull too little or too much causing you not to feel suction properly. You can get your correct flange size for free on Zomee's website! 💕 2. Your pump parts may be worn out and it’s time for a replacement. The Duckbill valve and diaphragm should be swapped out every 2-3 months. 💕 3. Begin your pumping session using the stimulation mode to encourage letdown, then switch to the expression mode. Use the adjustable suction levels to find what’s most comfortable and effective for you. The Zomee Fit features 9 levels of stimulation, 9 levels of expression, and a 2-phase mode to mimic the way a baby feeds, providing you with customizable options for your comfort and increased milk flow.💙

What the mamas said ⬇️⬇️ First I want to say, discovering the invaluable wisdom from seasoned moms was the secret sauce that smoothed my breastfeeding journey. Stay tuned for the pearls of wisdom shared by our community of moms!! 🔔THE RESPONSES🔔 “I wish I could tell myself that it may be hard at first, but it’s so worth it in the end” “I wish I was easier on myself instead of comparing myself to everyone who breastfed longer than I did” “Just to trust the process and I wish I had something that made it easier to store milk without spilling it” “Take more pictures!” “I would tell myself to not give up because it takes time to adjust. My breast pump made my life easier because it made the milk flow consistently” “I wish I used my pump more” “I wish i could’ve kept going or got a lactation consultant” “Breast feeding is the hardest job you’ll EVER do. It’s all on you, but you have to stick with it. After 2 or 3 months it gets significantly easier. And not having to warm and clean a bottle in the middle of the night is amazing! - With pumping I wish someone had told me to refrigerate the pump parts instead of washing them every single time. It would have saved me a LOT of time.” If you need any assistance navigating your breast-feeding journey, or selecting the perfect products to implement these tips, our DM‘s are always open! These boots were made for... fighting for maternal rights. 👢 Yesterday was a big day for Willow and moms everywhere. Our CEO, Sarah O'Leary, joined @chamberofmothers in DC to advocate for the passage of the Maternal Health Momnibus Act and kick off a critical conversation about motherhood. They spoke with six members of Congress and garnered bi-partisan support for legislation that would support federal paid leave, affordable childcare, and an end to the maternal mortality crisis that takes far too many lives. This work couldn't matter more — especially in a year when women's health is on the ballot. Moms deserve support when raising their families, and they're finally starting to demand it. We're proud to amplify their voices in the Capitol and beyond and plant seeds for a better future for families nationwide. Want to join our movement? Get involved! The second day post delivery may take you by surprise! Baby is more awake and alert than the day before! Here’s a helpful breakdown to help you through day 2 of breastfeeding: • Feeling: Sleep-deprived & sore. Purelan nipple cream is your friend! • What's Happening? Cluster feeding! Your baby's helping your milk supply grow. Expect 2 wet and 2 poopy diapers. • What to Do? Seek lactation consultant for help! A good latch is key. Also, keep up that skin-to-skin contact! Your little one needs a lot of it during the first few days. • What Success Looks Like: Focusing on yourself and your baby, and don’t be shy about reaching out early on to a professional for help with latching and learning to breastfeed. ✨Tip: Keep in mind that you may arrive home before your full milk supply comes in, so you still need to frequently feed. Once settled in at home, lean on your support systems and ask for help! Remember to limit visitors right now to only those who want to help! (Bring dinner, do laundry, help with dishes, etc.)

Traveling while pumping moms here are tips to travel safely with your breastmilk. Always plan ahead when traveling with your breast milk. 💼 Use insulated cooler bags with ice packs to keep the milk cool. Make sure the milk containers are tightly sealed. ✈️ If you're flying, check the airline's policies on carrying breast milk. Most airlines allow it, but it's good to be aware of any specific rules they might have. Inform security officers that you're carrying breast milk. They might need to inspect it separately. Consider freezing the milk before your trip. Safe Holidays moms! #motifmedical #breastmilkstorage #breastmilktravel #milksupply

Heading home with your little one? Learn how to manage potential engorgement and support your breastfeeding journey. • Feeling: Exhausted & feeling extra-vulnerable and sensitive – It's okay! • What's Happening? Welcome home, mama! You may have had a crazy night! Your baby is eating a lot and may not be sleeping much. Colostrum begins to transition into mature milk and can cause uncomfortable engorgement. Expect about 3 poops and 3 wet diapers. • What to Do? Compresses & massage with our Organic Breast Massage Oil can help with engorgement. • What Success Looks Like: Embracing the idea of around-the-clock feeding on demand (totally normal in these early days!), with the knowledge that breastfeeding won’t always be this hectic. ✨Tip: If you’re worried that your milk isn’t coming in about 72 hours after birth, talk to your healthcare provider and check out some of our tips. Practice kangaroo care (skin-to-skin). It benefits you & baby.

How to do Kegels properly Kegel exercise is exercising your pelvic floor by contracting and relaxing the pelvic floor muscles. 1. Empty your bladder 2. Get comfortable either on a chair or lying down 3. Locate your pelvic floor muscles (imagine you’re trying to hold your urine mid-flow but without squeezing your buttocks or inner thighs) 4. Tighten your pelvic floor muscles and count for 3-5 seconds 5. Relax your pelvic floor muscles and count for 3-5 seconds 6. Repeat this 10x - up to 3x per day (morning, afternoon, evening) You might only be able to tighten your pelvic floor for one second to begin with but as you practice it should improve! You can find out more about the Elvie Trainer on our website. It can help you make sure you’re doing Kegels correctly (30% do it incorrectly). It guides you through each exercise on an app and gameifys the experience. #elvie #kegel #kegels #pelvicfloor #pelvicfloorexercises

Let’s talk let downs! 🥛✨ Ever feel that delightful tingle or rush of milk? That’s your body saying, 'milk’s on the way!' 🙌 When your baby nurses, they start with quick, shallow sucks to stimulate milk release, then shift to deeper, longer sucks as they drink. Our Harmony hand pump is designed with two handles to mimic this natural sucking pattern: the top handle is for stimulation mode, featuring shorter, faster pulls, while the bottom handle is for expression mode, allowing for longer, deeper pulls! 🔔 Did you know 🔔 you can experience multiple let downs in a single pump session! Can you feel your let down? 🤱✨

"Proof that breastfeeding in public is not some new, disrespectful, immoral, and shameful secret act that only needs to be done at home, behind closed doors, or under a blanket 🤷🏾‍♀️ The kids did not care, the other moms didn’t care, the husbands/bfs/ and partners minded their business, and the non parents gave 0 cares as well!! My comment section when I post about breastfeeding and doing it comfortably without a cover in public are ALWAYS filled with men, women, and other mothers alike, scolding, ridiculing, and shaming me for it. But I have yet to encounter any such people in public. I know they’re out there and I’m blessed to have never encountered them but the way the Instagram folks flock to the comments to condemn me you’d think it would be the same in the real world 🤔 To any mama nervous about doing this, don’t be mama. I support you and I hope this inspires some confidence! You do what makes you and your baby comfortable. ⚠️ Avoid microwaving breast milk! ⚠️ Microwaving can heat up your breast milk unevenly, which may destroy key nutrients and change the composition of your breast milk, making it less beneficial for your baby. Plus, there could be hotspots in the milk, burning your baby’s mouth! 🔥 Instead, protect all that liquid gold by defrosting it in the fridge, warming it in a bowl of lukewarm water, or using a breast milk warmer. The first FIVE days are crucial for building a strong milk supply. Don’t get discouraged if you’re not filling up bottles just yet—you're not supposed to be! If you're only getting a few drops or a few mLs, that’s completely normal and part of the process. It’s important to continue breastfeeding, pumping, or hand expressing during these early days to help “program” your body and brain for a successful breastfeeding journey ahead. Stay patient and keep up with your frequent feedings/pumping sessions!🤱

Can you overfeed your baby? 🥛 Yes you can! Overfeeding is more likely to happen when you bottle-feed baby When breastfeeding, babies have to work harder for their milk 💪 helping them regulate their intake naturally. It’s like sucking through a straw—steady but with effort! This allows breastfeeding to be preventative for obesity and high BMI On the other hand, bottle feeding offers a constant flow of milk, similar to a hose, making it easier for babies to overfeed 😋 To help prevent this, hold the bottle horizontally and watch for signs of fullness. Look for a relaxed body and that adorable milk buzz! If your baby seems tense or stiff, they might still be hungry!

Here’s how I increased my supply by fixing some common pumping mistakes! (And the 3rd one made a BIG difference!) I know the struggle of under-supplying—here’s what helped me: 1️⃣ Flange size matters! The flanges that come with your pump may not be the right fit. Measuring your nipple size and using the correct flange or inserts can improve milk removal and comfort. 2️⃣ Empty your breasts fully! Milk supply works on a demand basis—if milk isn’t removed effectively, your body may reduce production over time. 💡 Pro tip: Pump for a few extra minutes after your breasts feel empty. This signals your body to keep producing! 3️⃣ Optimize your pump settings! A high-quality pump that fully empties your breasts can make a big difference. (More suction ≠ more milk—find a comfortable setting that works for you!) ❌ Some moms find that certain wearable pumps don’t fully empty their breasts, which may impact supply. ✅ When I switched to the BabyBuddha pump and improved my technique, I saw a noticeable increase in my output! 💪 Now, I’m pumping more efficiently than ever! Save these tips to help you simplify your milk storage routine using the pitcher method: 1️⃣ Gather Supplies: Use a 24-32oz food-grade container with a spout and lid. 2️⃣ Stay Clean: Wash hands, clean your pump, and prep your containers. 3️⃣ Collect Milk: Pump or express milk into the container. 4️⃣ Label It: Note the date of the oldest milk if pooling over 24 hours. 5️⃣ Prep Bottles: Use pooled milk for feedings or prep as needed. 6️⃣ Freeze Extras: Store extra milk in our freezer-safe milk storage bags or bottles. 🎉 Celebrate YOU! 𝐃𝐢𝐝 𝐲𝐨𝐮 𝐤𝐧𝐨𝐰 𝐲𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐦𝐢𝐥𝐤 𝐬𝐮𝐩𝐩𝐥𝐲 𝐢𝐬 𝐡𝐢𝐠𝐡𝐞𝐬𝐭 𝐢𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐦𝐨𝐫𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠? 🌅 This is because 𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐥𝐚𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐧, the hormone that makes milk, is at its highest between 𝟐 𝐚.𝐦. 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝟓 𝐚.𝐦. Your body naturally produces more milk during these early hours. As the day goes on, prolactin levels drop. This means your milk supply will 𝐠𝐫𝐚𝐝𝐮𝐚𝐥𝐥𝐲 𝐝𝐞𝐜𝐫𝐞𝐚𝐬𝐞 throughout the day. By evening, your breasts may feel softer, and your pump output may be lower—𝐭𝐡𝐢𝐬 𝐢𝐬 𝐜𝐨𝐦𝐩𝐥𝐞𝐭𝐞𝐥𝐲 𝐧𝐨𝐫𝐦𝐚𝐥! 𝐓𝐡𝐢𝐬 𝐝𝐨𝐞𝐬 𝐍𝐎𝐓 𝐦𝐞𝐚𝐧 𝐲𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐬𝐮𝐩𝐩𝐥𝐲 𝐢𝐬 𝐥𝐨𝐰. Your body is still making plenty of milk, just in smaller amounts. Your baby may nurse more often in the evening, and if you pump, you might get less per session. But the total amount of milk you make over 24 hours usually stays the same! 𝐖𝐚𝐧𝐭 𝐭𝐨 𝐤𝐞𝐞𝐩 𝐲𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐬𝐮𝐩𝐩𝐥𝐲 𝐬𝐭𝐫𝐨𝐧𝐠? ✔️ 𝐏𝐮𝐦𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐚𝐭 𝐧𝐢𝐠𝐡𝐭 𝐨𝐫 𝐞𝐚𝐫𝐥𝐲 𝐦𝐨𝐫𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠 can help maximize output. ✔️ 𝐃𝐨𝐧’𝐭 𝐬𝐤𝐢𝐩 𝐦𝐨𝐫𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐩𝐮𝐦𝐩 𝐬𝐞𝐬𝐬𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬—this is when you get the most milk! ✔️ 𝐄𝐯𝐞𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐜𝐥𝐮𝐬𝐭𝐞𝐫 𝐩𝐮𝐦𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐠 (shorter, more frequent sessions) can help if you need to collect more. So if you notice less milk later in the day, 𝐝𝐨𝐧’𝐭 𝐬𝐭𝐫𝐞𝐬𝐬! This is just how your body works. 💛 𝐊𝐞𝐞𝐩 𝐩𝐮𝐦𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐠, 𝐤𝐞𝐞𝐩 𝐟𝐞𝐞𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠, 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐭𝐫𝐮𝐬𝐭 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐜𝐞𝐬𝐬! 💪 Go give @cassiansmommy a follow!

Getting the right flange size is one of the most important steps in protecting your supply and your comfort. Here’s how to check: ▪️ Measure your nipple before a pump session, not the areola ▪️ Use a silicone nipple ruler—we recommend the one from @bemybreastfriend ▪️ Watch for signs your flange is off: pain, rubbing, swelling, or low output If you're using our pump and unsure about your size, we can help! What are diaphragms (aka backflow protectors)? They keep milk and moisture out of your tubing + pump motor. Clean pump = safer milk + stronger suction. 🗓 Replace every 8–9 weeks ⚠️ Or sooner if: • Suction feels off • You see moisture inside • Parts look cloudy or stretched Small part, big job. ✈️ Flying while pumping? Here’s what you need to know before heading to the airport with your breast pump and milk: 1️⃣ You don’t need your baby with you in order to bring breastmilk with you through TSA. Breastmilk, formula, and pump gear are allowed even if you’re traveling solo. 2️⃣ Breastmilk is exempt from the 3.4 oz liquid rule. You can carry larger amounts—just let TSA know ahead of time. 3️⃣ Frozen milk, ice packs, and gel packs are allowed. Even if partially thawed. Let TSA that you need your breastmilk to be kept at a certain temperature so it doesn't harm of your baby. 4️⃣ Your pump is medical equipment. It does not count toward your carry-on limit. 5️⃣ Bring printed TSA & airline policies. Not every agent knows the rules—having them on hand ready to go helps. 6️⃣ Use a cooler bag or insulated pouches to keep milk cold while traveling. 7️⃣ Request a visual inspection if you don’t want milk going through the X-ray. TSA is required to accommodate. 8️⃣ Pack smart. Keep pump parts organized in a clean travel pouch or wet/dry bag. Bring extra pump parts and your chargers. 📝 Always double check with your airline. Each airline has their own policy for medical equipment, carry-ons, and coolers—so it’s best to call ahead. 📄 And don’t forget to keep a printed copy of the most current TSA guidelines in your bag just in case. ✨ Save this post for your next trip! Here’s why: ▪️ 𝐍𝐚𝐭𝐮𝐫𝐚𝐥 𝐬𝐮𝐧𝐥𝐢𝐠𝐡𝐭 𝐡𝐞𝐥𝐩𝐬 𝐲𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐛𝐨𝐝𝐲 𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐝𝐮𝐜𝐞 𝐯𝐢𝐭𝐚𝐦𝐢𝐧 𝐃, which plays a role in mood regulation and energy levels. ▪️ 𝐁𝐞𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐨𝐮𝐭𝐝𝐨𝐨𝐫𝐬 𝐜𝐚𝐧 𝐥𝐨𝐰𝐞𝐫 𝐜𝐨𝐫𝐭𝐢𝐬𝐨𝐥 (your stress hormone) and help reset your nervous system. ▪️ 𝐅𝐫𝐞𝐬𝐡 𝐚𝐢𝐫 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐮𝐫𝐚𝐥 𝐥𝐢𝐠𝐡𝐭 𝐬𝐮𝐩𝐩𝐨𝐫𝐭 𝐛𝐞𝐭𝐭𝐞𝐫 𝐬𝐥𝐞𝐞𝐩, which is often disrupted during postpartum. ▪️ 𝐄𝐯𝐞𝐧 𝐚 𝐬𝐡𝐨𝐫𝐭 𝐜𝐡𝐚𝐧𝐠𝐞 𝐢𝐧 𝐞𝐧𝐯𝐢𝐫𝐨𝐧𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐭 𝐜𝐚𝐧 𝐡𝐞𝐥𝐩 𝐫𝐞𝐝𝐮𝐜𝐞 𝐟𝐞𝐞𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐠𝐬 𝐨𝐟 𝐢𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧, especially if you’re home all day with your baby. If you’re exclusively pumping or working from home, stepping outside for one of your sessions can offer both a mental and physical reset. No elaborate self-care needed. Breastmilk is not one-size-fits-all. Your body makes milk that’s tailored to your baby’s age, stage, and needs. As your baby grows, your milk naturally changes: - More fat - More calories - Different immune support And yes—this still happens even if you’re not nursing at the breast. Your body responds to hormones, your baby’s age, and even exposure to their saliva (from skin-to-skin, kisses, or contact) to adjust what your milk provides. It’s not “just milk.” It’s dynamic, living nutrition—made just for your baby.

Noticing changes in your milk supply around 3 months? Don’t panic—this is totally normal! 👇 At around 3 months postpartum, your body adjusts to start making the amount your baby needs—no more, no less. This is called 𝗺𝗶𝗹𝗸 𝘀𝘂𝗽𝗽𝗹𝘆 𝗿𝗲𝗴𝘂𝗹𝗮𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻, and it can feel like a sudden "dip," but it’s not a true decrease in supply! Here’s what’s normal: ✔️ 𝗠𝗼𝗿𝗲 𝘁𝗶𝗺𝗲 𝗯𝗲𝘁𝘄𝗲𝗲𝗻 𝗳𝗲𝗲𝗱𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘀 – Baby is more efficient at nursing. ✔️ 𝗦𝗼𝗳𝘁𝗲𝗿 𝗯𝗿𝗲𝗮𝘀𝘁𝘀 – Your body isn’t overproducing anymore. ✔️ 𝗠𝗼𝗿𝗲 𝗺𝗶𝗹𝗸 𝗶𝗻 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗺𝗼𝗿𝗻𝗶𝗻𝗴, 𝗹𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗮𝘁 𝗻𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 – Natural hormone shifts and regulation. ✔️ 𝗟𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗸𝗶𝗻𝗴 – Your supply has balanced out. ✔️ 𝗤𝘂𝗶𝗰𝗸𝗲𝗿 𝗳𝗲𝗲𝗱𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘀 – Baby gets milk faster. ✔️ 𝗟𝗲𝘁𝗱𝗼𝘄𝗻𝘀 𝗳𝗲𝗲𝗹 𝗹𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗲𝗻𝘀𝗲 – But they’re still happening! ✔️ 𝗣𝘂𝗺𝗽𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗼𝘂𝘁𝗽𝘂𝘁 𝗺𝗮𝘆 𝗱𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝗮𝘀𝗲 – Pumps aren’t as efficient as babies. 💡 𝗥𝗲𝗴𝘂𝗹𝗮𝘁𝗲𝗱 𝘀𝘂𝗽𝗽𝗹𝘆 ≠ 𝗹𝗼𝘄 𝘀𝘂𝗽𝗽𝗹𝘆! As long as baby is having plenty of wet/dirty diapers and gaining weight, your body is doing exactly what it should. baby’s first flight from sf to south korea ✈️ overall he mostly slept on the flight, the only hard part was putting him to sleep since he has fomo and wants to play 😂 will and i were prepared and check-in and tsa at the airport went pretty smooth 😮‍💨 here’s what help us have a smoother experience at the airport: • give yourself plenty of time to get the the airport and to be at the airport • bring a baby carrier so you can wear your baby through security and boarding. (i used @mabecarriers) • check stroller and car seat at the gate. get covers for it so it won’t get damaged • feed baby or pacifier during take off and landing • pack a lot diapers and extra clothes for baby and yourself. never know when there will be an accident • bring baby’s favorite toys to keep them entertained • get tsa precheck and/or clear • you can bring breastmilk, formula, and a cooler bag (great if you if you need to pump on the flight) #babytravel #travelingwithababy #babysfirstflight #infanttravel #travelvlog #familytravel #5monthold #southkorea #seoul

✈️ Flying while pumping? Here’s what you need to know before heading to the airport with your breast pump and milk: 1️⃣ You don’t need your baby with you in order to bring breastmilk with you through TSA. Breastmilk, formula, and pump gear are allowed even if you’re traveling solo. 2️⃣ Breastmilk is exempt from the 3.4 oz liquid rule. You can carry larger amounts—just let TSA know ahead of time. 3️⃣ Frozen milk, ice packs, and gel packs are allowed. Even if partially thawed. Let TSA that you need your breastmilk to be kept at a certain temperature so it doesn't harm of your baby. 4️⃣ Your pump is medical equipment. It does not count toward your carry-on limit. 5️⃣ Bring printed TSA & airline policies. Not every agent knows the rules—having them on hand ready to go helps. 6️⃣ Use a cooler bag or insulated pouches to keep milk cold while traveling. 7️⃣ Request a visual inspection if you don’t want milk going through the X-ray. TSA is required to accommodate. 8️⃣ Pack smart. Keep pump parts organized in a clean travel pouch or wet/dry bag. Bring extra pump parts and your chargers. 📝 Always double check with your airline. Each airline has their own policy for medical equipment, carry-ons, and coolers—so it’s best to call ahead. 📄 And don’t forget to keep a printed copy of the most current TSA guidelines in your bag just in case. ✨ Save this post for your next trip! Comment below if you’ve ever pumped while flying—we’d love to hear your tips too! 👇

Noticing changes in your milk supply around 3 months? Don’t panic—this is totally normal! 👇 At around 3 months postpartum, your body adjusts to start making the amount your baby needs—no more, no less. This is called 𝗺𝗶𝗹𝗸 𝘀𝘂𝗽𝗽𝗹𝘆 𝗿𝗲𝗴𝘂𝗹𝗮𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻, and it can feel like a sudden "dip," but it’s not a true decrease in supply! Here’s what’s normal: ✔️ 𝗠𝗼𝗿𝗲 𝘁𝗶𝗺𝗲 𝗯𝗲𝘁𝘄𝗲𝗲𝗻 𝗳𝗲𝗲𝗱𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘀 – Baby is more efficient at nursing. ✔️ 𝗦𝗼𝗳𝘁𝗲𝗿 𝗯𝗿𝗲𝗮𝘀𝘁𝘀 – Your body isn’t overproducing anymore. ✔️ 𝗠𝗼𝗿𝗲 𝗺𝗶𝗹𝗸 𝗶𝗻 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗺𝗼𝗿𝗻𝗶𝗻𝗴, 𝗹𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗮𝘁 𝗻𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 – Natural hormone shifts and regulation. ✔️ 𝗟𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗸𝗶𝗻𝗴 – Your supply has balanced out. ✔️ 𝗤𝘂𝗶𝗰𝗸𝗲𝗿 𝗳𝗲𝗲𝗱𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘀 – Baby gets milk faster. ✔️ 𝗟𝗲𝘁𝗱𝗼𝘄𝗻𝘀 𝗳𝗲𝗲𝗹 𝗹𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗲𝗻𝘀𝗲 – But they’re still happening! ✔️ 𝗣𝘂𝗺𝗽𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗼𝘂𝘁𝗽𝘂𝘁 𝗺𝗮𝘆 𝗱𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝗮𝘀𝗲 – Pumps aren’t as efficient as babies. 💡 𝗥𝗲𝗴𝘂𝗹𝗮𝘁𝗲𝗱 𝘀𝘂𝗽𝗽𝗹𝘆 ≠ 𝗹𝗼𝘄 𝘀𝘂𝗽𝗽𝗹𝘆! As long as baby is having plenty of wet/dirty diapers and gaining weight, your body is doing exactly what it should. No need to stress! 💕If you have any concerns please consult with your pediatrician.

Feeling a little less like a fumbling newbie? This is around the time breastfeeding starts to feel more comfortable and natural. Feeling: More comfortable and confident! Breastfeeding is becoming less work and more bonding time. What's Happening: You're getting the hang of this! Your baby is nursing efficiently and your milk supply is regulating. Your baby will gain weight – about 5 – 7 ounces weekly! You’ll see about 3 – 5 poops and 6 or more wet diapers. What to Do? Continue feeding your little one frequently, about 8 – 12 times daily, especially if they’re experiencing another growth spurt. If you’re getting bored at home, try breastfeeding in different environments to see what you’re most comfortable with. What Success Looks Like: You’re settling into breastfeeding – and maybe even enjoying it – while forming a vision of how your breastfeeding routine will work for your family. ✨Tip: If you’re looking for a comfortable and versatile nursing bra, give our Keep Cool Bra collection a try!

Heading home with your little one? Learn how to manage potential engorgement and support your breastfeeding journey. Feeling: Exhausted & feeling extra-vulnerable and sensitive – It's okay! What's Happening? Welcome home, mama! You may have had a crazy night! Your baby is eating a lot and may not be sleeping much. Colostrum begins to transition into mature milk and can cause uncomfortable engorgement. Expect about 3 poops and 3 wet diapers. What to Do? Compresses & massage with our Organic Breast Massage Oil can help with engorgement. What Success Looks Like: Embracing the idea of around-the-clock feeding on demand (totally normal in these early days!), with the knowledge that breastfeeding won’t always be this hectic. ✨Tip: If you’re worried that your milk isn’t coming in about 72 hours after birth, talk to your healthcare provider and check out some of our tips. Practice kangaroo care (skin-to-skin). It benefits you & baby.

A little self-care goes a long way, mama. Take a moment to recharge while the Swing Maxi Hands-Free pump works its magic. Whether it’s a walk outside or just a breath of fresh air, finding balance makes all the difference for you and your baby. 🌿💛

Time for your baby's first checkup? Celebrate milestones and get tips for continued breastfeeding success! Feeling: More confident (even if tired)! You're a rockstar, mama! What's Happening? If pumping hurts, something’s probably off. Here are a few common reasons why: ▪️ Your flange might not be the right size ▪️ The suction might be turned up too high ▪️ Your pump parts might not be placed correctly ▪️ Your nipples could be dry, cracked, or already sore What can help: ▪️ Measure your nipples to make sure you have the right flange size ▪️ Start on a low suction setting and only increase if it feels okay ▪️ Try silicone flanges if you have sensitive nipples ▪️ Use nipple cream or pump spray to help with the friction If the pain doesn’t go away, reach out to an IBCLC or lactation consultant. Pumping should never feel painful and you deserve support.

Here’s what you should know about caffeine while breastfeeding: ▪️ Up to 300 mg of caffeine per day is considered safe for breastfeeding moms that’s about 2–3 cups of coffee depending on the strength ▪️ Only a small amount of caffeine passes into your breastmilk The good news? You don’t have to give up your favorite cup. Just enjoy it in moderation. If you ever have concerns, check in with your pediatrician or IBCLC for peace of mind.

Tag a pregnant mom! Here’s everything a parent needs to know when breastfeeding a newborn. Feeling: Like Superwoman! 🦸‍♀️ Exhausted, but you conquered childbirth! What’s Happening? Colostrum arrives - tiny amount but mighty! Baby is super sleepy - Skin-to-skin time is key! (This helps the baby wake up!) Expect 1 wet & 1 poopy diaper. What to Do? Nurse frequently & ask for help! You’re not alone, mama. 💛 What success looks like: Even if your baby’s latch isn’t great, hand expressing drops of colostrum is still okay! Lots of rest for mama and baby after labor and delivery! ✨ Tip: Every breastfeeding journey is unique. You’ve got this!
